Day 1 – Networking Fundamentals
What is Networking

Networking is the connection of multiple computers or devices so they can communicate and share data with each other.

The purpose of networking:

Share data

Share resources (printer, storage, server)

Enable communication (email, web, apps)

Example: In a company, all computers are connected through a network to access the same database server.

What is the Internet

The Internet is a global network of networks.

It connects millions of private and public networks across the world using standard communication protocols.

Simple meaning:
Networking = connection between devices
Internet = worldwide connection of networks

How the Internet Actually Works

When you open a website:

You type a domain name (example: google.com).

DNS converts domain name into IP address.

Your request travels through routers across networks.

It reaches the server where the website is hosted.

Server sends response back to your system.

Your browser displays the webpage.

Internet works using:

IP addressing

Routers

DNS

Protocols like TCP/IP

What is an IP Address

An IP address is a unique logical address assigned to a device in a network.

It helps identify:

Who is sending data

Who is receiving data

Example:
192.168.1.1

Without IP address, communication is impossible.

Types of IP Address

Public IP
Used on the Internet. Globally unique.

Private IP
Used inside local networks. Not directly accessible from Internet.

Private IP ranges:

10.0.0.0 – 10.255.255.255

172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255

192.168.0.0 – 192.168.255.255

Static IP
Does not change.

Dynamic IP
Automatically assigned and changes.

What is CIDR

CIDR means Classless Inter-Domain Routing.

It is used to define IP address range using slash notation.

Example:
192.168.1.0/24

Here:

/24 means 24 bits are fixed for network

Remaining bits are for hosts

CIDR helps in efficient IP allocation and subnetting.

What is a Subnet

A subnet is a smaller network created from a large network.

Purpose:

Security

Isolation

Better management
Reduced broadcast traffic

Example:
192.168.1.0/24 can be divided into smaller subnets like:
192.168.1.0/26
192.168.1.64/26


Public Subnet
Has route to Internet Gateway. Resources can access internet.

Private Subnet
No direct internet access. Used for databases and internal services.


A port is a logical communication endpoint.

IP address identifies the device.
Port identifies the application on that device.

Port range:
0 – 65535

Well-known ports:

80 → HTTP

443 → HTTPS

22 → SSH

21 → FTP

What is a Protocol

A protocol is a set of rules that define how data is transmitted between devices.

Without protocol, devices cannot understand each other.

Types of Protocol

Transport Layer Protocol

TCP
Connection-oriented
Reliable
Data guaranteed
Used for web, email, file transfer

UDP
Connectionless
Faster
No guarantee of delivery
Used for streaming, gaming, DNS

Internet Layer Protocol

IP (Internet Protocol)
Responsible for logical addressing and routing of packets.

ICMP
Used for error reporting and diagnostics (example: ping).

